  - name: employee_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of employee non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Alaska sets no statutory cap on duration; enforceability turns on the fact-bound Data
      Management reasonableness factors rather than a fixed number. 24 months matches the modal
      employee non-solicit term observed in benchmarked, publicly-filed employee agreements; 12
      months is the common lighter alternative, and counsel should size the term to the employer's
      actual protectable interest.
  - name: covered_employee_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which employees are covered by the
      non-solicitation restriction.
    display_label: Covered Employee Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for employee non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the customer/partner non-solicitation covenant is included
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Included
    default: true
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of customer/partner non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Alaska sets no statutory cap. Metcalfe upheld a narrow customer-list
      restraint even without a stated durational limit, but a stated period is
      easier to defend; 12 months is a common, conservative duration counsel
      should size to the actual customer relationships protected.
  - name: covered_customer_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which customers are covered by the
      non-solicitation and non-dealing restrictions.
    display_label: Covered Customer Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for customer non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: noncompete_included
    type: boolean
    description: >-
      Whether the non-competition covenant is included. Alaska has no general
      non-compete statute; a non-compete is enforceable only to the extent it is
      reasonably necessary to protect a legitimate business interest and no
      broader than needed under the Data Management reasonableness factors, and
      it is strictly construed. This template recites the protectable-interest
      basis and sizes the restraint to the employer's actual footprint.
    display_label: Non-Competition Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Conservative default. The non-compete is the most heavily scrutinized
      covenant — Alaska strictly construes non-competition agreements and a
      restraint aimed at ordinary competition or the worker's livelihood fails
      the factors no matter how modest its time and territory look. A customer
      non-solicit backstopped by the Alaska Uniform Trade Secrets Act often
      protects the employer as well. Include only after confirming an identified
      protectable interest (confidential information, trade secrets, or customer
      goodwill) and sizing the duration and territory to the actual footprint.
  - name: noncompete_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-competition restriction
    display_label: Non-Competition Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Alaska imposes no statutory cap on duration; time limits are one Data
      Management factor among many, weighed together with territory against the
      employer's real protectable interest, so there is no safe-harbor number.
      12 months is a common, conservative default counsel should size to the
      actual role and market rather than copy from another form.
  - name: territory
    type: string
    description: Geographic scope of the non-competition restriction
    display_label: Restricted Territory
    default: the geographic area in which Employee provided services
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Tied to the employee's actual service area. Alaska imposes no statutory cap
      on territory and a statewide covenant is not automatically invalid, but
      every mile must map to the business interest at stake; a narrower area
      genuinely needed to protect customer relationships or confidential
      information is far easier to defend as good-faith drafting than an
      unexplained statewide ban.
  - name: competitive_business_definition
    type: string
    description: >-
      Description of the business activities that constitute competition with
